	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>THE DARKNESS AND THE BALANCE III--ENTER THE DARKNESS</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><p><b>Chapter 3—Enter the Darkness</b></p>

<p>A horse galloped into the village.  The rider was worn out.  Sweat drenched him and his steed.  He spoke through gasps of breath and had an intent stress in his voice. </p>

<p> “Is Garlin here?” </p>

<p>Garlin heard his name being called outside the hut where they were all preparing to leave.  He stopped helping and went to the caller.  When he left the hut, he saw the half-elf Walkin. </p>

<p> “Hello my friend.  What brings you to this dark wood?” </p>

<p>Walkin struggled for breath. </p> 

<p> “Freeport is under attack by some sort of dark magical beasts.” </p>

<p> “Surely the guards can handle it….can’t they?” </p>

<p> “They are doing what they can but many have already been slaughtered.  It is a magic with which our wizards and magicians are unfamiliar.  It seems to be being helped along by some greater force and it carries with it the stench of darkness.” </p>	

<p>Garlin tensed when he heard the word darkness.  He became acutely aware of the feeling in the air and decided action must be taken. </p>

<p> “And so it begins.” </p>

<p>He walked back into the hut. </p>

<p> “My friends, your trip to see Sir Vislin will have to be delayed.  I fear the darkness has begun.  Go to Freeport and see what you will shortly face.” </p>

<p> “Nonsense!! We go to see Tarn.  We must set out now!” </p>

<p> “No Zarx!  If you do not find out what you are up against and stop these small invasions there will be no reason for you to carry on further.” </p>

<p>Zarx knew that Garlin was right. </p>

<p> “Very well.  We shall prepare for battle and move on to Kithicor after we have dealt with this nuisance.” </p>

<p> “Zarx I speak only with respect, but do not underestimate the powers that be.  As soon as you do, we are all doomed.  Gaan you will attend them.  Be prepared little one and you may need this.” </p>

<p>Garlin pulled a shining blue sword out from under a bed.  It was wrapped in wolf skin and it seemed to shimmer from inside when he removed it from the skin.  It was almost as if it were alive.  Gaan stared at it in awe. </p>

<p> “It…ah…will serve you well.” </p>

<p> “I know it will.  And you Zeryl, take this.” </p>

<p>He reached into a box and handed Zeryl a crown encrusted with many jewels.  It sparkled even in the hut. </p>

<p> “You may not feel that you are the chosen but this will aid you regardless.” </p>

<p> “Enough with the gifts! Let us go!” </p>

<p>Zarx set out and without another word; the others followed. </p>

************************************************************************
<p>Kozo brushed off the dust from his robe as he appeared in the western part of the Commonlands.  He sniffed the air with disgust.  Nidus rested on his shoulder. </p>

<p> “This fresh air stuff will kill a gnome.” </p>
<p>He stepped from the platform he had transported to and noticed smoke coming from Freeport City.  Curiosity overtook him as usual and he set out for the city.  </p>

<p> “Come Nidus. Let us check this out.” </p>

<p>--Do I have a choice?— </p>

<p>Kozo ignored the bird’s snide comment and continued on to Freeport. </p>

************************************************************************
<p>The docks had been set on fire.  As Zarx and his company moved into Freeport, smoke filled their lungs.  They saw very little due to the smoke and searched for any sign of life.  Bodies lay on the ground and buildings that were not crushed, were boarded shut.  Zarx drew his sword and sniffed the air.  Gaan had already drawn the blue sword.  Ndarye’s hands glossed over with blue light.  Helfgar held his spear at the ready.  A huge dog like creature leapt out from behind some of the rubble. </p>  

<p> “Duck!!” </p>

<p>But Zeryl was too late. The dog jumped on him and sank its teeth deep into his arm.  Zarx was the first to react.  He sank his sword deep into the creature’s belly.  It fell over dead.  Zeryl’s arm healed as Ndarye finished her spell. </p> 

<p> “Looks like we’ll have to be on our toes.” </p>

<p> “Yes, but if they are all the weak we shall dispatch them quickly.” </p>

<p> “Zarx, look at the buildings.  I doubt we see many more rapid animals.” </p>

<p>The group moved on.  They heard a rumbling coming from the western part of Freeport.  The increased their pace and when they rounded the corner they were met with a scene of carnage.  A creature standing 25 ft tall stood in the middle of the courtyard surrounded by bodies. </p> 

<p>The creature was disgusting.  Its skin was barely clinging to its huge body.  Its dark black skin emitted a scent of death and decay.  It took no real form, almost ghost like but as it hacked away at the small people on the ground, it was obvious that it was not ethereal.  Screams pierced the air as the creature took life after life.  It seemed to grow stronger as it killed. </p> 

<p>Helfgar summoned a wolf spirit to assist them as they seemed to have no choice but to fight.  Gaan’s sword glowed brightly and almost pulled Gaan toward the creature. </p> 

<p> “Whoa Gaan.  This thing is huge we’re gonna have to take it down……”</p>

<p>The creature suddenly let out a loud cry.  It turned its back to Zarx and he charged, followed by the rest of them.  The creature stepped toward something.  In its back a huge hole had been made by something.  The flesh began to fill and Zarx became a little concerned.  But he reached the creature and shot upward.  He began his attack.  Mana surged through his body. </p>

<p>A wave of red mana flashed through the air as Zarx slashed into the dark body of the creature.  The creature flung its arm around striking Zarx squarely in the chest.  The touch of the creatures arm filled him with a sense of doom.  He lost feeling in his limbs as his body flew across the courtyard into the wall.  He landed and was immediately on his feet again thanks to Ndarye.  The feeling of dread hadn’t been cleansed from his system however. Gaan cut deeply with each hack.  The sword seemed to eat at the legs of the creature.  Zeryl closed his eyes sent a surge of energy right to the creature’s brain.  It stopped. </p>

<p>The creature seemed to stagger and almost fall over.  It turned its massive hulk to Zeryl and just stood and stared, if it could stare.  A bright flash came from behind and a loud explosion was heard behind the creature but it continued to stare at Zeryl.  Suddenly Zeryl fell to the ground and the creature slowly stepped toward him.  Zarx charged once again. </p>  

<p> “DENAC LUMOS!!” </p>

<p>Bright red mana flashed all around.  The creature staggered and fell to the ground.  Smoke rose from the creature’s body and Zarx fell to the ground.  Ndarye ran to him but seemed helpless.  </p>

<p> “He is drained.  I cannot help him.”  </p>

<p> “It is of no concern.  He will recover.” </p>

<p>Helfgar spoke with a distracted as he stared at the dead body on the ground and spoke to Ndarye.  He stepped closer and noticed a small person around the corner of the courtyard. Zeryl stirred on the ground and Gaan helped him up. </p>

<p> “You ok?” </p>

<p> “Yes.  There was a voice.  It said we shall not succeed.” </p>

<p>This got everyone’s attention and Zarx stood up. </p>

<p> “I heard no voice.” </p>

<p> “I heard it…..  Inside my head.  It communicated almost telepathically.  And it possessed much greater power than whatever that thing was did.  But I can’t explain it.” </p>

<p> “Perhaps the creature spoke to you.  Or you say it was something else?” </p>

<p> “I don’t know.  It just overcame me.  All I know is that it was powerful.” </p>

<p> “We shall prepare as necessary.  Let us not dwell on it. Let us go to meet our new found ally.” </p>

<p>Helfgar moved to the corner to find Kozo. </p>  

<p> “Hello there little one.” </p>

<p> “Ahem.  Hello sir;  I am Kozo. Nice to make your meeting.” </p>

<p> “That was quite a brave thing to be blasting a creature 10 times your size.” </p>

<p>”More like stupid.” </p>

<p>Zarx stared at the gnome.  Halflings were one thing, but gnomes were a whole other story.  Dirty little creatures which caused more trouble than good.  </p>

<p> “What brings you to Freeport?” </p>

<p> “The search of knowledge and saving grace.” </p>

<p> “Saving grace?” </p>

<p> “Yes.  I seek a man you would know nothing of.  I believe him to be in Kithicor.  I was on my way when I saw the smoke.” </p>

<p> “Ahh very well  we are headed that way ourselves.  Join us.” </p>

<p>Zarx rolled his eyes. </p> 

<p> “Bah barbarians, Halflings, and now gnomes, what will it be next.” </p>


<p>He watched with interest from his plane. </p> 

<p> “These mortals are quite entertaining.  Especially the one they call Zeryl.  It seems I can communicate within him.  This should prove to be useful indeed.” </p>

<p>He called upon some of his more powerful minions. </p>  

<p> “Go.  Let’s just see what this little conglomerate can do.  Spare none of them.  And do not fail me.” </p>

<p>Four creatures with huge wingspans took to the air to search for death, for they had not been denied in the past and had no plans to let their god down now. </p>
 </font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><small>By <b>Xzenus</b> Submited on 11/21/2001</small></td>
